This paper deals with graphical models and probability distributions, which are common topics in artificial intelligence and machine learning (cs.AI, cs.LG). The use of algorithms and optimization techniques (fractional linear programming) suggests that the paper may also belong to the information theory sub-category (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the properties of d-separation, which is a concept in causal inference and graphical models, making the sub-category cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) a likely fit. Finally, the paper's focus on detecting and exploiting independence relations suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category cs.SI (social and information networks).
